# New developments

### Purgatory
- Became officially endorsed by the church in 1253
	- "Purgatorial fire"
	- "souls of the pious are purified by temporary punishment"
	- "...so an entrance may be opened for them into the enternal country in which nothing stained can enter"
- This resolved some invonsistencies
- Provided an opportunity for the living to interact with the afterlife:
	- ...by praying for the souls in purgatory
	- ...to shorten the amount of time they have to spend there
	- This prayer is directed towards The Virgin Mary
		- the "Queen of Purgatory"
			- AKA "The intercessor"
		- Who people appeal to to aid those in purgatory
		- However, protestants later believed her to be a false idol
- Virtually everyone would go to purgatory
	- ...except the *extremely* virtuous/evil
- **Indulgences**
	- One could pay the church money to be forgiven for a sin
		- ...supposedly shortening their time in purgatory
		- Driving issue of the [[Protestant\|Protestant]] reformation

## Theater
- Roman theater was mostly stamped out by the church following the fall of the empire
	- Theater was strongly linked with the Roman gods
	- Strongly associated with prostitution
	- Featured actors, dialogue, plots
- Mystery plays
	- ~900s CE
	- Performance of biblical scnees
	- Stopped around [[Unsorted/The Rennaissance\|The Rennaissance]] when non-biblical theater became popular
	- Depictions of hell:
		- Often humorous, instance of [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes\|Merry Hell]]
			- Typically low-brow, or scatological humor
			- A way of grappling with the heavy, scary nature of these things
		- Frequently depicted [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes\|The Harrowing of Hell]]
		- Often centered around a [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes\|Hellmouth]]
			- Most elaborate stagecraft by far
			- Sometimes a mechanical device that could open and close
			- Smoke, flames, loud noises, bad smells

## Architecture
- Cathedrals
	- Most important element of cathedrals is the tympanum
		- Semicircular or triangular spaces above the top of doorways, which have been inset into structural archways
		- Great place to put art, since they're very visible and otherwise 
		- In one particular cathedral, one tympanum sculpture over 1000 years old was incredibly well preserved due to being plastered over in the 1700s
			- Used to be painted, but the paint has since come off
			- Depiction of last judgement
			- Features jesus and large clothed important figures
				- Incl. Peter
			- The saved:
				- Looking up at jesus
				- Some are being carried up and away by angels
			- The damned
				- Intricate and monstrous beasts
					- Gaping mouths, exposed teeth
					- Anatomical details, like bulging rib bones
					- One is throwing humans into a boiling cauldron
				- Primary demon is depicted with one half of a scale, which is the other half of one that goes towards the side of salvation
					- Shown to be cheating by pulling and weiging down the scale. Yanking down the scales, holding a human, with snakes on his legs and a bonus demon in the basket to weigh it down
